explanation:
For each symbol below I state why its semantics/implementation are required to decide whether code in ahc_echo is dead (i.e. executed but removable without changing program behaviour):

- struct Holder: needed to know which resources (FILE*, z_stream, buffer pointer) are owned and how they must be cleaned; determines whether the explicit cleanup path is redundant or required.  
- read_cb: required to know when (synchronously or later) it is invoked and whether it actually uses holder->file/stream/buf (so allocations/opens are needed for observable behaviour).  
- free_cb: required to know whether and when the response system will free holder and run cleanup (deflateEnd/fclose/free) so manual frees in error paths may be redundant (dead) or necessary.  
- MHD_create_response_from_callback: needed to know ownership and lifetime semantics (does it store the cls pointer, call read_cb immediately, register free_cb to be called on destroy) which affects whether creating holder and registering free_cb is required for program behaviour.  
- MHD_destroy_response: needed to know whether it invokes free_cb/other cleanup on the response and when that occurs (on success, on error return), to determine if the explicit cleanup or the call itself is dead.  
- MHD_queue_response: required to know whether queuing the response triggers immediate use of the callback or copies data (affects whether creating/opening/initializing holder before/after queue is observable) and whether removal would change behaviour.  
- MHD_add_response_header: needed to know whether adding headers has any side effects, whether it can fail in practice, and whether its return value can differ (so the conditional checks/gotos are meaningful vs dead).  
- deflateInit: required to know whether initializing the z_stream has observable effects and must be undone (deflateEnd) — i.e. whether deflateInit/deflateEnd pair are necessary for correct behaviour or are redundant.  
- deflateEnd: needed to know whether it performs required cleanup (so explicit calls are necessary) or is a no-op (making some cleanup dead).  
- fopen: needed to know if opening __FILE__ has observable effects (file access) and whether read_cb depends on the FILE; if fopen is never used later, the open could be dead.  
- fclose: required to know whether explicit close is necessary or if ownership is transferred so explicit fclose would be redundant.  
- malloc: needed to know whether buffer allocation size (CHUNK) and existence are required by read_cb/MHD internals or can be omitted without changing behaviour.  
- free: required to determine whether manual frees duplicate frees performed by free_cb/MHD_destroy_response (double-free risk) or are necessary.  
- CHUNK: size of the buffer allocation; needed to judge whether the allocation is meaningful for observable behaviour (e.g., affects amount of data delivered or causes no-op).  
- MHD_SIZE_UNKNOWN: semantics matter (how the response framework treats unknown-size callbacks) — affects whether callback consumption is used and so if holder setup is necessary.  
- MHD_HTTP_HEADER_CONTENT_ENCODING / MHD_HTTP_HEADER_CONTENT_TYPE: header names used; needed to know if adding those headers changes observable behaviour (client-visible) and thus whether the calls are dead.  
- MHD_HTTP_OK: HTTP status used with MHD_queue_response; required to understand whether the queued response changes observable behavior (status sent), and whether queuing is required.

In short: to decide if any lines in ahc_echo are dead you must know the ownership, lifetime, synchronous/asynchronous invocation, and side-effects of the response APIs and the callbacks/resources (Holder, read_cb, free_cb) and the behaviour of zlib/file/buffer operations; the listed symbols provide that necessary information.
